{{Infobox power station | name = Caorso Nuclear Power Plant | image = Carso_NPP_1.jpg | image_caption = Outside view of the plant, 2005 | location_map = Italy | status = B | operator = [[Societa Gestione Impanti Nucleari|SOGIN]] | coordinates = {{coord|45.07206|N|9.87214|E|region:IT_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | np_reactor_type = BWR | ps_units_decommissioned= 1 × 860&nbsp;MW | ps_electrical_capacity = 860 | construction_began = 1968–1970 | commissioned = January 1, 1970 | decommissioned = 1990 }}
'''Caorso Nuclear Power Plant''' was a [[nuclear power plant]] at [[Caorso]] in [[Italy]]. It featured a single [[Boiling Water Reactor]], a BWR 4 with a Mark II-[[Containment building|Containment]] from [[General Electric]], with an electrical net output of 860 MW, used low-enriched [[uranium]] as fuel, was moderated and cooled by normal light water.
It operated from 1981 until 1990, when it was closed following the [[Italian nuclear power referendum, 1987|referendum]] of November 1987. It was by far the most modern and in terms of capacity biggest nuclear power plant to go online in Italy.
