{{Infobox power station | name = F-1 | name_official = Physics-1 | image = RIAN archive 500897 Control panel of the first Russian nuclear reactor.jpg | image_size = 250px | image_caption = Control panel of the reactor | image_alt = | location_map = Russia | location_map_size = | location_map_caption= | coordinates = {{coord|55|47|46|N|37|28|43|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://wikimapia.org/229565/F-1-Nuclear-Reactor|title=F-1 Nuclear Reactor Moscow|publisher=Wikimapia|accessdate=25 December 2010}}</ref> | country = Soviet Union, now Russian Federation | location = Moscow | status = Permanent Shutdown | construction_began = 15 November 1946 | commissioned = 26 December 1946 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = Russian Research Centre, Kurchatov Institute | operator = Russian Research Centre, Kurchatov Institute | np_reactor_type = Graphite Pile | np_reactor_supplier = Russia | ps_units_manu_model = | ps_electrical_capacity= | ps_electrical_cap_fac= 24 kWt | website = | extra = |th_fuel_primary =46411kg of natural uranium metal (UO<sub>2</sub> and U<sub>3</sub>O<sub>8</sub>) |th_fuel_tertiary =41kg of 2% enriched uranium }}
The '''F-1''' is a [[research reactor]] operated by the [[Kurchatov Institute]] in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]. When started on December 25, 1946, it became the first [[nuclear reactor]] in Europe to achieve a self-sustaining [[nuclear chain reaction]].<ref name="f1-nwa">{{cite web|url=http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/Russia/Russreac.html|title=The World's Oldest Operating Reactor: The Russian F-1|work=The Nuclear Weapon Archive|accessdate=25 December 2010}}</ref> It was still in operation in the beginning of the 2010s, with a power level of 24 [[Watt#Kilowatt|kW]], making it, at that time, the world's oldest operating reactor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nti.org/db/nisprofs/russia/reactor/research/with/kurchato.htm#f1|title=Division of System Analysis Elektronika Information and Computer Complex Engineering and Production Division|last=Vakhroucheva|first=Elizaveta|work=[[Kurchatov Institute]]|publisher=NTI|accessdate=25 December 2010}}</ref> In November 2016 it was in permanent shutdown state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nucleus.iaea.org/RRDB/RR/HeaderInfo.aspx?RId=318|title=IAEA Research Reactor Database|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref>
