{{infobox winter storm |name= |image location=Nor'easter_1995-02-05_weather_map.jpg |image name=A [[surface weather analysis]] of the nor'easter |stormtype=[[Nor'easter]] |date formed=February 2, 1995 |date dissipated=February 6, 1995 |RSI=4.28 |pressure={{convert|962|mbar|inHg|abbr=on}} |maximum amount= |total damages (USD)= |total fatalities= |areas affected= }}
The '''February 1995 Northeast United States snowstorm''' was a significant [[nor'easter]] that impacted the [[Mid-Atlantic States|Mid-Atlantic]] and [[New England]] regions of the [[United States]] around the beginning of the month.<ref name="snowfall">{{cite web|author=|title=Rank: 10 &#124; 5 February 1995 &#124; Score: 134.15|date=|publisher=Lyndon State College|accessdate=January 6, 2010|url=http://apollo.lsc.vsc.edu/projects/snowstorm/}}</ref> It was the only major nor'easter of the 1994–1995 winter.<ref name="Kocin2">Kocin and Uccellini, p. 590</ref>
==Synoptic history== The initial [[low pressure area]] tracked eastward from the southern [[Great Plains]] on February 2. Gradually intensifying, it was situated over eastern [[Kentucky]] by 0000 UTC on February 4. As the system entered [[West Virginia]], a secondary low began to develop over [[South Carolina]]. The new low quickly deepened, and absorbed the primary low over West Virginia into its expanding and strengthening circulation. It continued to rapidly mature as it moved northward from eastern [[Maryland]],<ref name="Kocin2"/> and it hugged the coast as it moved northeastward towards southern [[New England]].<ref name="graphic">{{cite web|author=|title=February 04–6 Observed Liquid Precipitation|date=|publisher=Lyndon State College|accessdate=January 6, 2010|url=http://apollo.lsc.vsc.edu/projects/snowstorm/Images/LowTracks/19950204_tname_LIQUID.gif}}</ref>
The cyclone reached a strength of 980 [[millibars]] while located south of [[Long Island]]. It crossed eastern New England and reached its peak intensity, with a minimum barometric pressure of 962 mb, over eastern [[Maine]]. Prior to the nor'easter, an [[high pressure area|area of high pressure]] drifted southeastward from north of the [[Great Lakes]], producing sufficient cold air to support snow throughout the Northeast. However, as the storm intensified, precipitation near the coast, including the major cities of [[Philadelphia]], [[New York City|New York]], and [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], changed to rain. Due to the lack of a strong [[anticyclone]] at the surface, winds in association with the system were minimal until after the storm abated.<ref name="Kocin2"/> Behind the nor'easter, high winds, sufficient to bring down trees and powerlines, occurred.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for New York: High Winds|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 5, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~219105}}</ref>
==Impact== Snow from the nor'easter was heavy and widespread. Areas that picked up {{convert|10|in|mm|abbr=on}} or more include [[Pennsylvania]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[New Jersey]], [[Connecticut]], [[Massachusetts]], [[Vermont]], [[New Hampshire]] and [[Maine]]. Scattered reports of {{convert|20|in|mm|abbr=on}} were received in upstate New York and northern Vermont.<ref name="Kocin2"/> At [[Burlington, Vermont]], {{convert|16.8|in|mm|abbr=on}} of snow fell, beating the daily record of {{convert|8.7|in|mm|abbr=on}} set in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for Vermont: Heavy Snow|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 5, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~244067}}</ref> Overall, the event ranks as a category 2 on the [[Northeast Snowfall Impact Scale]].<ref name="Kocin2"/>
In Pennsylvania, the heaviest snow fell in [[Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Bucks County]]. Throughout the state, the number of traffic accidents was minimized due to the storm's arrival on a weekend. Three died of cardiac arrest after shoveling snow, and more than 100 people were hospitalized for chest pain. Several dozen more were injured after slipping and falling on ice, and 53 residents sustained snowblower-related injuries.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for Pennsylvania: Heavy Snow|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 5, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~230899}}</ref> At least 18 people were injured in nearby New Jersey, where the maximum snow accumulation was reported to be {{convert|16|in|cm}} in [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for New Jersey: Heavy Snow|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 5, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~217292}}</ref> Along the coast, minor to moderate coastal flooding occurred, along with some [[beach erosion]]. Some areas lost power for several hours as fallen tree branches downed power lines.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for New Jersey: Coastal Flooding|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 5, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~217179}}</ref> The cyclone also produced heavy snow and coastal flooding in New York.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for New York: Coastal Flooding|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 5, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~219139}}</ref>
