{{Infobox company | name = Multinet Gas | logo = 2018 Multinet Gas Logo .png | industry = Natural Gas Distribution | hq_location_city = Melbourne, Victoria | area_served = Eastern Melbourne and South Gippsland | parent = [[Cheung Kong Infrastructure]] | website = Multinetgas.com.au }}'''Multinet Gas''' is an [[Australia]]n energy company and one of three [[Victoria (Australia)|Victorian]] [[natural gas]] distribution networks.
Multinet Gas distributes natural gas to more than 690,000 customers throughout [[Melbourne]]'s [[List of Melbourne suburbs|inner eastern suburb]]s and outer Eastern Suburbs, the Yarra Ranges, and South Gippsland. The network comprises 175km of licensed Transmission Pipelines, 9,959km of distribution mains (operating at pressures between 7kPa and 515 kPa), and 258 regulator stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.multinetgas.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/MG-2018-to-2022-Access-Arrangement-Information-211216-FINAL-1.pdf|title=2018 to 2022 Access Arrangement Information - Multinet Gas|last=Narvaez|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
The Multinet Gas area has over 200km of low pressure (7 kpa) gas mains, some of which are [[Ductile iron pipe|cast iron]] mains that date back to the 1880s. These older cast iron mains are subject to water ingress during wet weather and as such, are the common cause of supply reliability issues. Multinet Gas' mains Replacement Program is aimed at replacing low-pressure gas distribution mains in the network and is targeting to replace all low-pressure mains by 2033. Upgraded low-pressure mains are typically replaced with high-pressure polyethylene gas mains by inserting the new ductile [[High-density polyethylene|polyethylene pipe]] into the existing cast iron main. This method minimizes damage to property and offers additional protection to the polyethylene mains.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=View source for Multinet Gas|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Multinet_Gas&action=edit|journal=Wikipedia|language=en}}</ref>
== History == [[File:Multinet Gas Distribution Area Map 532x532.jpg|thumb|301x301px|Multinet Gas' distribution Area]]Gas networks were first built in Melbourne by the [[Metropolitan Gas Company]] some time before the 1880's<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/people/523942?c=people|title=Metropolitan Gas Company (Melbourne, Vic.). (-1950) - People and organisations|website=Trove|language=en|access-date=2018-02-05}}</ref>. In 1951 the Metropolitan Gas Company was taken over by the government-owned monopoly supplier, the [[Gas and Fuel Corporation of Victoria]] (G&FC). G&FC owned the Melbourne gas network area from 1951 until the privatization in 1997.
The company is owned by the [[DUET Group]], which was purchased in 2017, by [[Cheung Kong Infrastructure]] (CKI) for A$7.4 billion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/business/energy/electricity/firb-approves-cheung-kongs-duet-acquisition-20170420-gvp0bk|title=FIRB approves Cheung Kong's DUET acquisition|date=2017-04-21|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-02-19|language=en-US}}</ref> CKI controls other energy networks in Australia, including [[United Energy]], an electricity distributor in Melbourne's eastern and south-eastern suburbs and the [[Mornington Peninsula]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unitedenergy.com.au/our-story-and-vision/|title=About Us {{!}} United Energy|website=www.unitedenergy.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-02-19}}</ref> [[CitiPower]] in Melbourne; [[Powercor]] in western Melbourne and western Victoria; and [[Envestra]], which distributes gas through Victoria, [[Queensland]] and [[South Australia]].<ref name="age040917">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/melbournes-electricity-and-gas-facing-greater-chinese-control-20170409-gvh84k.html|title=Melbourne's electricity and gas facing greater Chinese control|last=Gordon|first=Josh|date=2017-04-09|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2018-02-19}}</ref> After the acquisition, CKI controls three out of five electricity distributors and two out of three gas distributors in Victoria.<ref name=age040917/> As of 2018, Multinet Gas is operated as a part of Australian Gas Infrastructure Group (AGIG) in conjunction with the other CKI owned Australian gas distribution Networks.
