'''Tetrafluorohydrazine''' or dinitrogen tetrafluoride, {{nitrogen|2}}{{fluorine|4}}, is a colourless, reactive [[inorganic compound|inorganic]] [[gas]]. It is a [[Fluorination|fluorinated]] analog of [[hydrazine]]. It is a highly hazardous chemical that explodes in the presence of [[organic compound|organic]] materials.
Tetrafluorohydrazine is manufactured from [[nitrogen trifluoride]] using an [[iron]] catalyst or [[iron(II) fluoride]]. It is used in some [[chemical synthesis|chemical syntheses]], as a precursor or a [[catalyst]].
Tetrafluorohydrazine was considered for use as a high-energy liquid [[oxidizer]] in some never-flown [[rocket fuel]] formulas in 1959.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070312051306/http://stinet.dtic.mil/oai/oai?&verb=getRecord&metadataPrefix=html&identifier=AD0313998 Tetrafluorohydrazine] at DTIC.mil archived March 12, 2007</ref>
