The '''Wiardunek''' (also referred to as '''wiardunk''', '''czwartak''' or '''ferton'''; {{lang-de|'''viertel'''}},{{sfn|Einsle|pp=122-124}} {{lang-la|ferto}}) was a [[Middle Ages|Mediaeval]] [[Central Europe|Central European]] unit of mass most widely used in [[Poland]] and [[Germany]].{{sfn|Einsle|pp=122-124}} Wiardunek was also used as a [[unit of account]], and as a such as [[commodity money]].

As a unit of mass 1 wiardunek (ca. 49 [[gram|g]]) was equivalent to 1/4 of [[Grzywna (unit)|grzywna]].{{sfn|Szwagrzyk|pp=51, 58–60}} Two [[ounces]] made up one wiardunek, and in turn each ounce consisted of two [[Lot (unit)|lots]]. 

As a unit of currency, the wiardunek was introduced probably around 14th century, first in Bohemia and then in other Central European states.{{sfn|Szwagrzyk|pp=51, 58–60}} This usage followed the same scheme as for other commodities, that is 1 wiardunek of pure silver was equivalent to 1/4 of grzywna, which in turn was composed of 64 [[groschen]].{{sfn|Szwagrzyk|pp=51, 58–60}} This usage was true regardless of changes in overall weight of grzywna, which was the basic unit of mass in this system.{{sfn|Szwagrzyk|p=51}}
{{money-unit-stub}} 

